Turkey’s Diplomatic Horizons Spread
Long before Turkey began to try to join the European Union, European powers longed to penetrate deep into Turkey's entanglement.
On the eastern bank of the Bosporus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, one of the best monuments to this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Con in a Neo-Renaissance style.
Then that's what the tourist guide will tell you.
The building sits at the end of the platforms with a tower on every corner of the façade, looking at the undistinguishable from some provincial German town hall.
The stone's dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once you get inside the vault, you can no longer have any doubt about the size of the business whose westernmost gate the station was.
In August 1908, the German consortium Anatoli-Bagada Corporation opened the station.
Germany, which was late in the game of empires, intended to implement its ambitions to take over the Middle East by means of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond to the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their dorms were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
Relative isolation from surrounding areas, created by the frozen Cold War border, is gone.
British and colonial forces advanced from Egypt and forced the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And bad news also came for Hydarpasha Station.
In 1917, an explosion of an ammunition train destroyed its sophisticated roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, they have been crumbling and history has been surrounding it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the widening horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from surrounding territories, created by the frozen Cold War border, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is engaged.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the leading experts of the AKP on foreign policy, the Turkish MEP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a gnarly ride on the tracks that reminded the ancient rhythms of the famous documentary Night Post, I arrived at the Turkish capital, designed as a new city for the secular state, who wants to turn his back on his Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a shift in the paradigm of the Turkish consensus.
In the west, she aroused suspicions, especially in Washington.
The taxi brought me to the main tent of AKP, an ultramodern stone and metal building, deliberately built in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power stores, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to do early morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a center-right politician from almost any other European political party.
The jacket, the tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The purpose of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey to its immediate surroundings.
Cold War was an anomaly," he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its entanglement.
Today they must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
It had to do both.
"But there will certainly come a time," I asked, "when may Turkey have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "didn't want that decision to happen."
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to said almost by heart: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea are as good for Europe and the United States as Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, ride these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of those two German masters Herr Ritter and Herr Con who watched this building be built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to find out that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East can now, for the most part, be in Turkish hands.
And while I was waiting at the port for the ferry back through Bospora, I remembered that in those days, Turkey was called "a sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
