"Auto bee" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan was inspired in nature, specifically with bees, to develop technologies to protect against accidents.
This Japanese company created a robot that takes the role of flying bees and thus prevents collisions.
This is Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Centre for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. robot developed in cooperation with the Centre for Progress in Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhir Doie, Director General of Public Relations for Brand Technology, Research and Development, BR23C is presented as an extension of four safety shield zones of Nissan.
The robot is tasked with enhancing the ability to prevent collisions in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan security shield.
But the most important are compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual function, engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are located up to two meters in a radius of 180 degrees before the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment the obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics bee movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even greater angle to prevent collisions.
The biggest difference compared to any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If that were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobile Laboratory and Chief Engineer of this project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move upwards and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction by which it is allowed to turn its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as with bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent collisions by robots.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and to maintain the data.
It does not require information retention or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, which allows it to function without interruption with only two dozen kB memory.
It may surprise you, but in memory, we're not talking about a gig or a mega."
This is the first step in the development of new collision prevention technologies, a technology where Nissan predicts use for serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination and avoid obstacles along the way.
