The Egyptian commando took an attack from the kidnappers of 11 tourists and their eight-man escorts who were captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for ten days, were alive on Monday and safely transported to the Egyptian capital.
They were liberated by an Egyptian commando in Chad during the morning.
Hostages arrived around 15.30, apparently in good form, on board a special aircraft to a military base al-Maza, closely adjacent to the Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred without being able to comment in the press, on board helicopters to a hospital in Maadi, the peripheral residential district of Cairo, to undergo medical examinations there.
"They are quite well" and "no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers", declared Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zohemir Garrana on the runway.
Since its capture on September 19 during the safari in a four-wheel drive at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the border of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages has been dragged from one hiding place to the other by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border director of Aegyptus agency, safari organizer.
A leader of Egypt’s security forces indicated that 30 special forces approaching the location on board two helicopters set off on the trail just before dawn.
"There was a shootout, half the kidnappers were killed and the others fled," said this source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He hinted that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian Special Forces from the "blink" unit were sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini, from Belgrade, where he is now, mentioned the role played by secret agents and the Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of people from our secret services, from special forces," he said without further clarification.
He also denied that the ransom would be paid.
On the eve before, the Sudanese army declared that on patrol, they intercepted a four-wheel-drive vehicle on which the kidnappers were on board, killing six of them, including the Chadian commander, and arrested two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a group of rebels in Darfur, the Movement for the Liberation of Sudan - Unity (SLA-U), which immediately rejected the movement.
