Benelux Governments of Fortis Bank
Benelux states will help Fortis, the Belgian-Dutch Bank, which was the first to get in trouble in Europe due to the spread of the US mortgage market crisis, by partial nationalization: three countries will support the money and insurance institution, which also has a capital participation in Hungary, with an amount of EUR 11.2 billion.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch Governments, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition, agreed to do so.
Fortis is the first in the euro area to have been in a major crisis in the context of the international financial market crisis, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions made in this matter could, from a certain point of view, be seen as precedents.
In the sense of the decision that was born on Sunday night, all three states will redeem almost half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets.
The bank will sell with absolute certainty part of its holdings, especially - mainly insurance - activities purchased last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Fortis bank shares started to fall sharply last week, and by the second half of the week, serious signs of the crisis were already emerging in the Institute.
Analysts agree, however, that with their 85 000 employees, the bank is too big to let it go bankrupt.
The company's securities fell by only 12 percent on Friday, at a minimum of 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current stock prices, the total market capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company leaders, this is unrealistic.
Moreover, the management blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the overseas market for the $700 billion US package’s acceptance of the plan.
On Monday, the stock went up slightly.
On Friday a new CEO Filip Dierckx was appointed to the head of the bank.
The money institution was also looking for private buyers, but with a more serious offer no one has ever signed up.
The Belgian Government has previously announced that investors do not have to worry, they will not lose their money.
There has been no panic among bank clients, and the branches have not been taken by attack.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also purchased several leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with applicants based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescription data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the fox's henhouse," quotes Washington Post Richard Dick, author of a program to monitor prescriptions.
Insurance companies shall make premiums and amounts paid in the event of insurance events dependent on the health of the candidates and shall not, if the risk is assessed as too large, enter into insurance with them.
They had previously sent the persons concerned for medical examinations and concluded the contract only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer identification number from the pharmacies, it is easy to find out what drugs the person has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself determines how he suffers from the disease and what his condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol - lowering drugs, this refers to having virtually uncontrolledly high levels of blood fats, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so there is almost no work left for the insurance company except for paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
Disadvantages include that many medicines can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
These represent a significant risk-increasing factor from the point of view of commercial insurance companies, whereas the first mentioned problems are not.
In order to request and process data, special companies were created to ask the patient for permission before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
The authorities are already forcing them to do so, even though they have not punished them for their negligence so far.
Some companies have recently processed the results of laboratory tests, which combine with data on the drugs used, thus providing an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to the data, while controlling their use will become increasingly difficult.
There is a special law for the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give the authorities the power to control even businesses specializing in data provision, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: that is why he has developed his program in such a way that the transfer of data is bound to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can hardly deny the permission in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not enter into a contract with him.
So, after all, the chickens are somewhat dependent on the fox's goodwill.
